Expert needed|Plants|date=January 2019
Plant communication encompasses all communication between plants and a host of other organisms such as soil microbes,<ref>Cite journal |last=Wenke |first=Katrin |last2=Kai |first2=Marco |last3=Piechulla |first3=Birgit|date=2010-02-01 |title=Belowground volatiles facilitate interactions between plant roots and soil organisms|url=https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/s00425-009-1076-2 |journal=Planta |volume=231 |issue=3 |pages=499–506|doi=10.1007/s00425-009-1076-2</ref> other plants<ref>cite journal |last=Yoneya|first=Kinuyo|last2=Takabayashi |first2=Junji |date=2014-01-01 |title=Plant–plant communication mediated by airborne signals: ecological and plant physiological perspectives|url=https://www.jstage.jst.go.jp/article/plantbiotechnology/31/5/31_14.0827a/_article|journal=Plant Biotechnology |volume=31 |issue=5 |pages=409–416 |doi=10.5511/plantbiotechnology.14.0827a</ref> (of the same or other species), animals,<ref>Cite journal|last=Leonard |first=Anne S. |last2=Francis|first2=Jacob S. |date=2017-04-01 |title=Plant–animal communication: past, present and future|url=https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/s10682-017-9884-5 |journal=Evolutionary Ecology| volume=31 |issue=2 |pages=143–151 |doi=10.1007/s10682-017-9884-5</ref> insects,<ref name=":1">Cite journal |last=De Moraes |first=C. M.|last2=Lewis |first2=W. J.|last3=Paré |first3=P. W.|last4=Alborn|first4=H. T.|last5=Tumlinson|first5=J. H.|title=Herbivore-infested plants selectively attract parasitoids|url=http://www.nature.com/doifinder/10.1038/31219 |journal=Nature|volume=393|issue=6685|pages=570–573|doi=10.1038/31219</ref> and fungi.<ref>Cite journal |last=Bonfante |first=Paola |last2=Genre |first2=Andrea|title=Arbuscular mycorrhizal dialogues: do you speak ‘plantish’ or ‘fungish’? |url=https://doi-org.offcampus.lib.washington.edu/10.1016/j.tplants.2014.12.002 |journal=Trends in Plant Science |volume=20 |issue=3|pages=150–154 |doi=10.1016/j.tplants.2014.12.002</ref> Plants communicate through a host of volatile organic compounds (VOCs) that can be separated into four broad categories, each the product of distinct chemical pathways: fatty acid derivatives, phenylpropanoids/benzenoids, amino acid derivatives, and terpenoids.<ref name=":2">Cite journal|last=Dudareva|first=Natalia|date=April 2013 |title=Biosynthesis, function and metabolic engineering of plant volatile organic compounds |url=https://www.jstor.org.offcampus.lib.washington.edu/stable/newphytologist.198.1.16 |journal=New Phytologist |volume=198 |pages=16–32</ref> Due to the physical/chemical constraints most VOCs are of low molecular mass (< 300 Da), are hydrophobic, and have high vapor pressures.<ref>Cite journal |last=Rohrbeck |first=D. |last2=Buss |first2=D.|last3=Effmert |first3=U. |last4=Piechulla |first4=B. |date=2006-09-01 |title=Localization of Methyl Benzoate Synthesis and Emission in Stephanotis floribunda and Nicotiana suaveolens Flowers |url=http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1055/s-2006-924076/abstract |journal=Plant Biology |volume=8 |issue=5 |pages=615–626 |doi=10.1055/s-2006-924076</ref> The responses of organisms to plant emitted VOCs varies from attracting the predator of a specific herbivore to reduce mechanical damage inflicted on the plant <ref name=":1" /> to the induction of chemical defenses of a neighboring plant before it is being attacked.<ref name=":0">Baldwin, Jan T., and Jack C. Schultz. “Rapid Changes in Tree Leaf Chemistry Induced by Damage: Evidence for Communication between Plants.”&nbsp;''Science'', vol. 221, no. 4607, 1983, pp. 277–279., www.jstor.org/stable/1691120.</ref> In addition, the host of VOCs emitted varies from plant to plant, where for example, the Venus flytrap|Venus Fly Trap can emit VOCs to specifically target and attract starved prey.<ref>Cite journal|last=Hedrich|first=Rainer|last2=Neher|first2=Erwin|date=March 2018|title=Venus Flytrap: How an Excitable, Carnivorous Plant Works|url=https://www.cell.com/trends/plant-science/pdf/S1360-1385(17)30280-7.pdf?code=cell-site|journal=Trends in Plant Science|language=English|volume=23|issue=3|pages=220–234|doi=10.1016/j.tplants.2017.12.004|issn=1360-1385</ref> While these VOCs typically lead to an increase in herbivory resistance in neighboring plants, there is no clear benefit to the emitting plant in helping nearby plants. As such, whether neighboring plants have evolved the capability to "eavesdrop" or whether there is an unknown tradeoff occurring is subject to much scientific debate.<ref>Cite journal|date=2010-03-01|title=Explaining evolution of plant communication by airborne signals|url=https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0169534709003000|journal=Trends in Ecology & Evolution|volume=25|issue=3|pages=137–144|doi=10.1016/j.tree.2009.09.010|issn=0169-5347</ref>

 Terpenoids 
File:Verbenone3D.png|thumb|The terpenoid verbenone is a plant pheromone, signalling to insects that a tree is already infested by beetles.<ref>cite book | last1=Mafra-Neto | first1=Agenor| last2=de Lame | first2=Frédérique M.  | last3=Fettig | first3=Christopher J. | last4=Perring | first4=Thomas M. | last5=Stelinski | first5=Lukasz L.  | last6=Stoltman | first6=Lyndsie L.| last7=Mafra | first7=Leandro E. J. | last8=Borges | first8=Rafael | last9=Vargas | first9=Roger I. | chapter=Manipulation of Insect Behavior with Specialized Pheromone and Lure Application Technology (SPLAT®) | title= Natural Products for Pest Management | editor=John Beck |editor2=Joel Coats |editor3=Stephen Duke |editor4=Marja Koivunen | publisher=American Chemical Society | volume=1141 | pages=31–58 | year=2013</ref>
further|Terpenoid

Terpenoids facilitate communication between plants and insects, mammals, fungi, microorganisms, and other plants.<ref>cite journal |last=Llusià |first=Joan |last2=Estiarte |first2=Marc |last3=Peñuelas |first3=Josep |date=1996 |title=Terpenoids and plant communication |journal=Bull. Inst. Cat. Hist. Nat |volume=64 |pages=125–133</ref> Terpenoids may act as both attractants and repllants for various insects. For example, pine shoot beetles (''Tomicus piniperda'') are attracted to certain monoterpenes ( (+/-)-A-Pinene|a-pinene, (+)-Carene|3-carene and terpinolene) produced by Scots pines ''(Scots pine|Pinus sylvestris''), while being repelled by others (such as verbenone).<ref>cite journal |last=Byers |first=J. A. |last2=Lanne |first2=B. S. |last3=Löfqvist |first3=J. |date=1989-05-01 |title=Host tree unsuitability recognized by pine shoot beetles in flight |url=https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/BF01952042 |journal=Experientia |volume=45 |issue=5 |pages=489–492 |doi=10.1007/BF01952042|issn=0014-4754</ref>

Terpenoids are a large family of biological molecules with over 22,000 compounds.<ref>Cite book |url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/497430488|title=Dictionary of terpenoids |last=Hill |first=Ruaraidh |last2=Connolly |first2=J.D. |date=1991 |publisher=Chapman & Hall |year=1971 |isbn=041225770X |pages= |oclc=497430488</ref> Terpenoids are similar to terpenes in their carbon skeleton but unlike terpenes contain functional groups. The structure  of terpenoids is described by the biogenetic isoprene rule which states that terpenoids can be thought of being made of isoprenoid subunits, arranged either regularly or irregularly.<ref>cite journal |title=The isoprene rule and the biogenesis of terpenic compounds |first=Leopold |last=Ružička |journal=Cellular and Molecular Life Sciences |volume=9 |issue=10 |pages=357–367 |year=1953 |doi=10.1007/BF02167631 |url=https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007%2FBF02167631</ref> The biosynthesis of terpenoids occurs via the Non-mevalonate pathway|methylerythritol phosphate (MEP) and  Mevalonate pathway|mevalonic acid(MVA) pathways<ref name=":2" /> both of which include Isopentenyl pyrophosphate|isopentenyl diphosphate (IPP) and Dimethylallyl pyrophosphate|dimethylallyl diphosphate (DMAPP) as key compenents.<ref>Cite journal |last=McGarvey |first=Douglas J. |last2=Croteau |first2=Rodney |date=July 1995 |title=Terpenoid Metabolism |jstor=3870054 |journal=The Plant Cell |volume=7 |pages=1015–1026</ref> The MEP pathway produces hemiterpenes, monoterpenes, diterpenes, and volatile carotenoid derivatives while the MVA pathway produces sesquiterpenes.<ref name=":2" />

